    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv from the current directory. For each of the three numeric telemetry files (metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv) compute an aggregate summary grouped by (cmdb_id, KPI_name) where KPI_name is metric.kpi_name for metric.csv, trace.trace_name for trace.csv, and log.log_name for log.csv. For each group return: cmdb_id, KPI_name, count of points, min(value), 50th percentile (median) of value, 95th percentile of value, max(value), and mean(value). Limit each file's aggregated table to the top 20 rows sorted by count descending. Additionally, list the distinct cmdb_id values found in each file. For error_logs.csv, return the count of rows per cmdb_id and the earliest timestamp per cmdb_id (limit to top 20 cmdb_id rows sorted by count desc). Keep outputs compact and textual (no plots) and store full dataframes in kernel variables for later steps." }

{
    "analysis": "From the previous step the Executor returned compact aggregate summaries for metric.csv, trace.csv and log.csv. Key observations: (1) Many component-KPI groups have 31 data points — this matches the incident window duration (00:00–00:30 inclusive) and suggests we have one-minute resolution covering the incident. (2) trace aggregates show IG01 and IG02 traces (trace.self.* and trace.to_Tomcat*.*) and indicate non-negligible p95/mean values. (3) log aggregates show Tomcat01 and Tomcat02 (and apache01/apache02) row_count and zero error_count in aggregates. (4) error_logs.csv appears empty. Based on rules, next we must compute global thresholds for each component-KPI using the full available series (before filtering) and then extract data within the incident window to detect anomalies. The next step will compute per-group P95 and P5, then find anomaly points in the incident time range (value >= P95 or value <= P5) and summarize anomaly counts and earliest anomaly timestamps for each group. This will narrow candidate faulty KPIs/components for deeper trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For metric.csv, trace.csv, and log.csv do the following and store intermediate full tables in kernel variables: 1) For each file, group by (cmdb_id, KPI_name) where KPI_name is kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, and log_name for log.csv. Using the entire available series for each group (do NOT filter by time yet), compute global_p95 and global_p5 for the 'value' column. 2) Then filter each original file to the incident time range: 2021-03-23 00:00:00 to 2021-03-23 00:30:00 in Asia/Shanghai timezone (Executor should handle timestamp parsing). 3) For each group, within the filtered window, identify anomaly points defined as value >= global_p95 OR value <= global_p5. For each group produce a compact summary row: cmdb_id, KPI_name, anomaly_count (number of anomaly points in window), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (Asia/Shanghai), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_p95, global_p5, and severity_ratio where severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window / global_p95) if anomalies are >=P95, else (global_p5 / min_value_in_window) if anomalies are <=P5. 4) Return for each file: top 20 groups sorted by anomaly_count desc (show the specified summary columns), total number of anomaly points in the file window, and a short list of groups with anomaly_count>0 (limit to top 50 names). Also keep the full anomaly-row tables in kernel variables for later inspection. Keep outputs compact and textual." }

{
    "analysis": "The Executor detected many anomalies across metrics, traces and logs in the incident window (2021-03-23 00:00–00:30+08). Key takeaways: (1) metric anomalies are widespread — e.g., many Mysql02 metrics and IG01 JVM memory metrics show anomaly_count=31 (every minute). (2) trace anomalies include IG01/IG02 and MG01 groups (duration and row_count breaches) with earliest anomalies at 00:00–00:02+08 and some high severity ratios (>2). (3) log.error_count groups are mostly zero and flagged because global thresholds are zero — these are not directly useful for magnitude-based severity analysis. According to the prescribed workflow, we must now perform fault identification on metrics: detect consecutive anomaly runs (faults) per component-KPI, filter out isolated spikes, and prioritize groups with sustained consecutive anomalies. This will narrow candidate root-cause components for downstream trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the previously stored full metric series and thresholds (use metric_window for the points within 2021-03-23 00:00–00:30 Asia/Shanghai and metric_thresholds for each group's global_p95 and global_p5), perform fault identification as follows: For each (cmdb_id, KPI_name) group, label a point as anomalous if value >= global_p95 OR value <= global_p5. Then detect consecutive-anomaly runs (consecutive minute timestamps with anomalous=True). For each group, compute: cmdb_id, KPI_name, total_anomaly_points (in window), max_consecutive_run_length, first_run_start_timestamp (Asia/Shanghai) for the longest run, first_run_end_timestamp, first_run_max_value (maximum value observed within that longest run), global_p95, global_p5. Filter to groups where max_consecutive_run_length >= 3 minutes (to remove isolated spikes). Return a compact table of the top 20 groups sorted by max_consecutive_run_length desc then total_anomaly_points desc (include the specified columns). Also return a list of distinct cmdb_id values present in these groups (limit to 20). Keep full per-point run detection results in a kernel variable for later inspection but only display the compact table and cmdb_id list." }

{
    "analysis": "We have completed metric-based fault identification. The metric analysis shows sustained (31-minute) faults across multiple node-level components: IG01, IG02, MG01, MG02 and Mysql02. These faults start at 2021-03-23 00:00:00+08 (earliest run start) and persist through the incident window. Many JVM memory KPIs and numerous Mysql02 KPIs are continuously beyond their global thresholds, indicating systemic resource deviations on those nodes. According to the diagnosis workflow, the next step is trace analysis to determine which faulty component is the most downstream faulty service/container in call chains (the typical root cause among multiple service-level faults). We should therefore inspect trace anomaly groups (within the same incident window) and map trace directions/peers (patterns like trace.to_X, trace.from_X, trace.self) to identify whether traces show calls flowing into one of the faulty nodes and to locate the last faulty node in those flows. The earliest anomaly timestamps on traces combined with metric fault start times will help pick the root cause occurrence time. I will now ask the Executor to produce a compact, parsed view of trace anomalies restricted to relevant candidate components and their peers so we can identify downstream faulty targets and earliest anomaly times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the stored trace anomaly results (trace_anomalies_full or trace_summary_full) do the following (keep outputs compact):\n1) Filter trace groups to those with anomaly_count>0 in the incident window. From each trace_name, parse a peer component and direction using these patterns: if trace_name contains 'to_<NAME>' then direction='to' and peer=<NAME>; if contains 'from_<NAME>' then direction='from' and peer=<NAME>; if contains 'self' then direction='self' and peer=cmdb_id. 2) From these filtered traces, keep only rows where either the trace row's cmdb_id OR the parsed peer is one of the metric-fault candidate cmdb_ids [IG01, IG02, MG01, MG02, Mysql02] (use the metric_runs_filtered cmdb_id list). 3) Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) sorted by anomaly_count desc then earliest_anomaly_timestamp asc showing: cmdb_id, direction, peer, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (Asia/Shanghai), max_value_in_window, severity_ratio. 4) Also return a short aggregate list of peers (peer name, count of trace-groups involving that peer, earliest trace anomaly timestamp for that peer) limited to top 20 peers. Keep the full filtered trace rows in a kernel variable for later inspection but only display the compact table and peer-aggregate list." }

{
    "analysis": "The trace-filtered results show anomalous call patterns involving MG01/MG02 and IG01/IG02, with peers including Tomcat01/Tomcat02 and dockerA/B. Metric fault identification already found sustained (31-minute) faults on multiple node-level components: IG01, IG02, MG01, MG02 and Mysql02 — all starting at 2021-03-23 00:00:00+08 and persisting through the incident window. According to the diagnosis rules, when multiple node-level faults exist for a single failure we should pick the predominant node(s) with the most faults as root-cause candidates, then use traces/logs to refine. To determine the predominant candidate(s) we need a compact, per-node summary from metric fault results (how many distinct KPIs per node had sustained faults, earliest fault start, and highest severity among its KPIs). This will let us prioritize which node to inspect further with traces and logs to identify the root cause reason and the exact occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the metric fault identification results (use metric_runs_filtered / metric_runs_summary_full), produce a compact per-cmdb_id summary limited to top 20 rows sorted by faulty_group_count desc. For each cmdb_id compute: cmdb_id, faulty_group_count (number of distinct KPI groups with max_consecutive_run_length >=3 in the incident window), earliest_fault_start_timestamp (Asia/Shanghai) among its groups, latest_fault_end_timestamp among its groups, and max_severity_ratio (maximum severity_ratio observed across its groups). Also include a short note column 'example_top_KPI' with the KPI_name of the single highest-severity group for that cmdb_id. Return only this aggregated table (top 20) and store the full grouping results in a kernel variable for later inspection." }

